{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/voice-to-text-with-chrome-web-speech-api-d98462cb0849", "time": 1683006672.2272708, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/voice-to-text-with-chrome-web-speech-api-d98462cb0849/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Voice to Text with Chrome Web Speech API | by Benson Ruan | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Voice to Text with Chrome Web Speech API", "description": "In this article, I am going to show you how to utilize Google Chrome's Web Speech API to build a web-app that can convert voice to text."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://w3c.github.io/speech-api/#speechreco-section", "anchor_text": "https://w3c.github.io/speech-api/#speechreco-section", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://github.com/bensonruan/", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/benson-ruan/", "anchor_text": "Linkedin", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["Since 2013, when Google Chrome released version 25, the support of Web Speech API opened up a whole new world of opportunities for web apps to convert voice to text.", "With the demo below, you can use Google Chrome as a voice recognition app and type long documents, emails and school essays without touching the keyboard.", "Try it yourself in the link below:", "You might be thinking \u201cfunctionality like Speech to Text is pretty complex to implement.\u201d Well, you\u2019d be right if you train the speech recognition model from scratch. But thanks to Google, they already did the hard work for you, by utilizing Chrome\u2019s built-in Web Speech API, you can turn your Chrome browser into a Voice to Text app. Let\u2019s explore more detail below.", "As you can see above, Chrome is the major browser that supports speech to text API, using Google\u2019s speech recognition engines.", "You can tell whether the browser supports the Web Speech API by checking if the webkitSpeechRecognition object exists.", "The next step is to create a new speech recognition object.", "The speech recognition object has many properties, methods and event handlers. For the full list, please refer to https://w3c.github.io/speech-api/#speechreco-section", "Below I would highlight the important parts for this application.", "When recognition.continuous is set to true, the recognition engine will treat every part of your speech as an interim result. When recognition.interimResults is set to true, interim results should be returned.", "Let\u2019s explore this recognition.onresult event below, to get more understand of what would be returned.", "The recognition.onresult event handler returns a SpeechRecognitionEvent which contains below fields:", "Chrome speech recognition supports numerous languages, If your users are speaking a language other than English, you can improve their results by specifying the language parameter recognition.lang", "By calling therecognition.start(), it activates the speech recognizer. Once it begins capturing audio, it calls the onstart event handler, and then for each new set of results, it calls the onresultevent handler.", "That\u2019s it! The rest of the code is just to enhance user experience. It shows the user some informative messages and swaps the GIF image on the microphone button.", "You can download the complete code of the above demo in the link below:", "The Web Speech API is very useful for voice control, dialog scripting, data entry. But at the moment among the major browsers, it is only supported by Chrome on desktop and Android phones. It would be good to see this great feature can be supported by other modern browsers in the future.", "Thank you for reading. If you like this article, please share on Facebook or Twitter. Let me know in the comment if you have any questions. Follow me on GitHub and Linkedin.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Diving into the world of Machine Learning and AI. Turning imagination into reality."], "all_outgo